FR940407-2-00097 FR940407-2-00052 Determinations Regarding Eligibility To Apply for Worker Adjustment Assistance and NAFTA Transitional Adjustment Assistance In accordance with section 223 of the Trade Act of 1974, as amended, the Department of Labor herein presents summaries of determinations regarding eligibility to apply for trade adjustment assistance for workers (TA&hyph;W) issued during the period of March, 1994. In order for an affirmative determination to be made and a certification of eligibility to apply for worker adjustment assistance to be issued, each of the group eligibility requirements of section 222 of the Act must be met. (1) That a significant number or proportion of the workers in the workers' firm, or an appropriate subdivision thereof, have become totally or partially separated, (2) that sales or production, or both, of the firm or subdivision have decreased absolutely, and (3) that increases of imports of articles like or directly competitive with articles produced by the firm or appropriate subdivision have contributed importantly to the separations, or threat thereof, and to the absolute decline in sales or production. Negative Determinations for Worker Adjustment Assistance In each of the following cases the investigation revealed that criterion (3) has not been met. A survey of customers indicated that increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,405; General Motors Corp., Inland Fisher Guide Div., Syracuse, NY TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,443; Posner Laboratories, South Plainfield, NJ TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,437; Philips Technologies, Airpax Protector Group, Frederick, MD TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,449; Hrubetz Oil Co., Westbrook, TX In the following cases, the investigation revealed that the criteria for eligibility have not been met for the reasons specified. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,501; Denim Finishers, Middlesboro, KY The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,454; Anchor Motor Freight, Inc., Champlain, NY ‚ê£2 The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,469; Thomas Cook Travel Money Services, Princeton, NJ The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,299; Control Techniques (USA), Inc. (E.C.S.), Fairmont, WV The predominate reason for the layoffs and closure of the subject facility was a decision by the parent company to consolidate production from the Fairmont location to another domestic affiliated facility. Affirmative Determinations for Worker Adjustment Assistance TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,494; Aileen's, South Hill, VA A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after February 2, 1993. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,485; Londontown Corp. (London Fog), Hancock, MD A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after January 12, 1993.
